<|startoftext|>Question:Can someone tell me how and where the term Cinco de Mayo is?
Answer:Cinco de Mayo is a national holiday celebrated in the United States. It is often celebrated in Puerto Rico.

The date of the event was set on November 21, 1825 and marked the start of the Spanish colonization in Louisiana's Caribbean region in 1609. On the day of the holiday, May 3, a small gathering of the Spanish colonials gathered at the site of St. Patrick's Cathedral (Puyallup on the mainland, located just outside of Louisiana) and danced in the streets to drum and dance to the tune of the national anthem, the American Revolution. A half hour later, the crowds of colonists joined in the celebration of the American Revolution.  

Cinco de Mayo may have been a regional celebration of a local holiday, but it was a festival in the American Colonies, and in the presence of the various tribes that lived in the colony. Although there were many local celebrations, the main focus of the celebration was the general celebration of the New York Island American Indians and their culture. On December 23, 1832, the colony of Puerto Rico celebrated its 100th birth celebration. The feast of the New York of the United States occurred on November 22, 1833, and came to be known as the ""Cinco de Mayo,"" although the island of Hispaniola may have been named for a famous Spanish colonist named Francisco Manuel de Arra, whom he had been a prisoner in the Spanish Revolutionary War.  The feast of the New York of the United States was also a holiday celebrated in other American cities and parts of Florida and Alaska. 

Cinco de Mayo is also used as more of a national holiday than any one of its counterparts:
The feast of the New York and other French colonies 
The first celebration of cinco de Mayo in a local American city was in 1769, in the aftermath of a revolt by the French against the presence of the French.  

